@Node "MainView" "MainActor.guide/MainView"
@Next "Tutorial"
@Prev "The Arexx Interface"
@Toc "Main"

MainView
********

   MainView is MainActors external player. It can display all
animations/pictures for which MainActor has the proper loader modules.

   The key commands while playing animations or showing pictures are
the same as if you would view them directly with MainActor.  Thats the
reason for not listing them here again, have a look at the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} under @{b}Play@{ub} and @{b}Show@{ub}.

   If MainActor saved an icon for the animations/pictures to view,
MainView will take the view settings from this icon (overruling its own
settings) !  You can change this behaviour through the @{b}IgnoreIcons@{ub}
option.

   You can start MainView from the workbench or form the cli.

@{b}Starting MainView from the Workbench@{ub}

   If you start MainView from the wb (per icon) you can select the
file(s) to view in an asl-requester. For multi selecting just press one
of the shift keys and select the files with the mouse. (Starting from
OS 2.1+)

MainView supports the following tooltypes:

@{i}Window@{ui}
     This tooltype enables the window mode, all animations or pictures
     will be displayed in an window on the current public screen.  It
     is disabled by default.

@{i}FrameInfo@{ui}
     FrameInfo enables the FrameInfo mode. It Is disabled by default.

@{i}NoCaching@{ui}
     Disables caching, with caching disabled MainView plays direct from
     the harddisk (or whatever). This allows you to play big animations
     even if you have not much ram.  It is disabled by default.

@{i}IgnoreIcons@{ui}
     Ignores the icons of the animations/pictures It is disabled by
     default.

@{i}Flash@{ui}
     Enables the Flash option. It is disabled by default.

@{i}XOffset=<Value>@{ui}
     You can directly set the start x offset.  Defaults to 0.

@{i}YOffset=<Value>@{ui}
     The same for the y offset.  Defaults to 0.

@{i}Repeat=<Value>@{ui}
     Repeats the animation <Value> times.  For example @{b}Repeat=1@{ub} would
     play the animation one time.  Defaults to 100.

@{i}Directory=<Path>@{ui}
     This is the initial directory for the asl-requester.

@{i}Anim_Module=<Module>@{ui}
     Chooses the default loader module for animations.  Default is the
     @{b}Universal@{ub} module.

@{i}Pic_Module=<Module>@{ui}
     Chooses the default loader module for pictures.  Default is the
     @{b}Universal@{ub} module.  If you want to view all pictures for example on
     the PicassoII gfx board, choose the @{b}Universal_PicassoII@{ub} module.

@{b}Starting MainView from the cli@{ub}

   Starting MainView from the cli will give you enhanced functionality.
You can for example define patterns for animations or picture lists.

   Usage is : MainView [-<options>] <file>

   You can enter as many files as you like.

MainView supports these options :

     -w           : enables the window mode
     -fi          : enables the frameinfo option
     -nc          : turns caching off
     -i           : ignore the icons for the animations/pictures
     -f           : enables the flash option
     -xvalue      : value describes the initial x offset
     -yvalue      : the same for the y offset.
     -rvalue      : value describes how often the animation
                    should be repeated
     -amodule     : where module is the default animation loader
                    for example @{b}-aUniversal@{ub} selects the universal
                    loader (default).
     -pmodule     : where module is the default picture loader
                    for example @{b}-aUniversal@{ub} selects the universal
                    loader (default).
                    If you want to remap your pictures to the
                    PicassoII board enter @{b}-pUniversal_PicassoII@{ub}

Examples:

@{b}MainView -nc -r1 Graphics:Pics/#? Animation/#?8_32@{ub} will show all files
in the Graphics:Pics/ directory as well as all files in the Animation/
directory which end with '8_32' and all animations will be directly
played from the harddisk (one time).

@{b}MainView -pUniversal_PicassoII Graphics:#?_24Bit@{ub} will display all
pictures which names end with '_24Bit' on the Picasso-II board.


@EndNode

@Node "Tutorial" "MainActor.guide/Tutorial"
@Next "Registration"
@Prev "MainView"
@Toc "Main"

Tutorial
********

   This tutorial will try to (quickly) explain the tasks you can
perform with MainActor.  It is just meant to give you the idea behind
MainActor, you have still to read all of the documentation to get the
most out of MainActor.

   ALL SAVE OR APPEND FUNCTIONS ARE DISABLED IF YOU DONT HAVE A KEYFILE
(DONT HAVE REGISTERED MAINACTOR YET).  THE TASKS YOU CANNOT PERFORM IF
YOU DONT HAVE A KEYFILE ARE MARKED WITH AN *.

@{b}This tutorial will tell you how to@{ub}


 @{" Load Animations " Link "Load Animations"} 
 @{" Load Picture(s) " Link "Load Picture(s)"} 
 @{" Play Animations " Link "Play Animations"} 
 @{" Show Pictures " Link "Show Pictures"} 
 @{" Create-Convert Animations " Link "Create-Convert Animations"}                 *
 @{" Save Pictures From Animations " Link "Save Pictures From Animations"}             *
 @{" Convert Picture Formats " Link "Convert Picture Formats"}                   *
 @{" Append To Animations " Link "Append To Animations"}                      *
 @{" Time Animations " Link "Time Animations"} 
 @{" Execute Arexx Scripts " Link "Execute Arexx Scripts"} 
 @{" Show Pictures-Animations On The PicassoII " Link "Show Pictures-Animations On The PicassoII"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Load Animations" "MainActor.guide/Load Animations"
@Next "Load Picture(s)"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Load Animations
===============

   You need an unused Project to load an animation into MainActor.
Select the @{b}Select Load Module@{ub} gadget of the @{"Project Window" Link "Project Window"} and select
the proper animation format (if you, for example, want to load an
@{"IFF-Anim5" Link "IFF-Anim5"} animation, select the IFF-Anim5 loader or the Universal
loader).  If you want to cache the animation (buffer the animation in
memory), enable the @{b}Caching@{ub} gadget. Now select the @{b}Load@{ub} gadget of the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} and select the animation in the opening asl
requester. MainActor will now examine the animation and load it into
memory (if caching is enabled).  After that the frames of the animation
are listed in the scroll list area of the project window, also all
gadgets (except the @{b}Load@{ub} and perhaps the @{b}Append@{ub} gadget) of the Project
Control Panel Window are now enabled.


@EndNode

@Node "Load Picture(s)" "MainActor.guide/Load Picture(s)"
@Next "Play Animations"
@Prev "Load Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Load Picture(s)
===============

   You need an unused Project to load a picture or a picture list into
MainActor.  Select the @{b}Select Load Module@{ub} gadget of the projects window
and select the proper picture format (if you, for example, want to load
an @{"IFF" Link "IFF"} picture, select the IFF loader).  If you want to cache the
picture(s) (buffer the picture(s) in memory), enable the @{b}Caching@{ub}
gadget. Now select the @{b}Load@{ub} gadget of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}
and select the first picture of the picture list in the opening asl
requester, if you want to load only one picture, you can cancel the
second requester, otherwise select the last picture of the picture list
in the second requester.  MainActor will now load the selected
picture(s) and buffer them into memory (if caching is enabled).  After
that the picture(s) are listed in the scroll list area of the project
window, also all gadgets (except the @{b}Load@{ub} and @{b}Play@{ub} and perhaps the
@{b}Append@{ub} gadgets) of the Project Control Panel Window are now enabled.


@EndNode

@Node "Play Animations" "MainActor.guide/Play Animations"
@Next "Show Pictures"
@Prev "Load Picture(s)"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Play Animations
===============

   You have to load an animation first.  Just click on the @{b}Play@{ub} gadget
of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}.  For further details have a look
into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Show Pictures" "MainActor.guide/Show Pictures"
@Next "Create-Convert Animations"
@Prev "Play Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Show Pictures
=============

   You have to load an animation or a picture list first.  Select the
pictures you want to show in the source projects list view gadget,
after that simply press the @{b}Show@{ub} gadget of the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}.  For further details have a look into the
documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Create-Convert Animations" "MainActor.guide/Create-Convert Animations"
@Next "Save Pictures From Animations"
@Prev "Show Pictures"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Create/Convert Animations
=========================

   You have to load an animation or a picture list first.  Select the
pictures who shall be included in the new animation in the source
projects list view gadget. After that select the @{b}Select Save Module@{ub}
gadget and select the proper animation format.  Now click on the @{b}Save@{ub}
gadget of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} and enter the name of the
new animation.  MainActor will then create the animation, you may have
to answer some requesters (looping or non looping animation and so on).
For further details have a look into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Save Pictures From Animations" "MainActor.guide/Save Pictures From Animations"
@Next "Convert Picture Formats"
@Prev "Create-Convert Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Save Pictures From Animations
=============================

   The procedure is exactly the same as before, just select a picture
save module instead of an animation module.  For further details have a
look into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Convert Picture Formats" "MainActor.guide/Convert Picture Formats"
@Next "Append To Animations"
@Prev "Save Pictures From Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Convert Picture Formats
=======================

   The procedure is exactly the same as before, just load a picture or a
picture list and select another picture formats save module.


@EndNode

@Node "Append To Animations" "MainActor.guide/Append To Animations"
@Next "Time Animations"
@Prev "Convert Picture Formats"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Append To Animations
====================

   Load an animation or picture list into the source project and an
animation into the destination project.  The name of the source
projects saver module has to equal the name of the destination projects
saver module (Beware of the Universal loader !!) The @{b}Append@{ub} gadget of
the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} should now be enabled. Select the
pictures you want to append (to the destination project) in the source
project. After that select the @{b}Append@{ub} gadget, MainActor will now append
the selected pictures of the source project to the animation in the
destination project.  For further details have a look into the
documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Time Animations" "MainActor.guide/Time Animations"
@Next "Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Prev "Append To Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Time Animations
===============

   Load an animation and select the pictures you want to give a new
timecode.  Now select the @{b}Select Timecode@{ub} item in the @{"Miscellaneous Menu" Link "Miscellaneous Menu"}
and enter the new timecode into the integer gadget.  MainActor will now
write the new timecodes to the animation, you can check the new
timecodes by playing the animation.


@EndNode

@Node "Execute Arexx Scripts" "MainActor.guide/Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Next "Show Pictures-Animations On The PicassoII"
@Prev "Time Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Execute Arexx Scripts
=====================

   You can directly execute arexx scripts by selecting the @{b}Start Arexx
Script@{ub} item in the @{"Arexx Menu" Link "Arexx Menu"} and selecting the arexx scripts.  You can
map arexx scripts to the function keys through the @{b}Install Arexx
Scripts@{ub} item (again in the Arexx Menu). You can really speed up
your work by using them, take a look at their header to get a short
description what they do.


@EndNode

@Node "Show Pictures-Animations On The PicassoII" "MainActor.guide/Show Pictures-Animations On The PicassoII"
@Prev "Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Show Pictures/Animations On The PicassoII
=========================================

   Just use the @{b}Universal_PicassoII@{ub} loader modules, they remap the
output of every module to the picasso board.  Note that it is faster to
view animations of the bitmap formats (like Anim-5,7,8) on the native
chipset as these formats have to be converted to the picassos chunky
pixel mode.


@EndNode

@Node "Registration" "MainActor.guide/Registration"
@Next "The Future"
@Prev "Tutorial"
@Toc "Main"

Registration
************

   The registration fee is @{b}$50@{ub} (85 german marks) or any aquivalent sum
in your local currency.

   You will get your keyfile per disk or email.  If you have an email
address, please include it in your letter.

   When the printed manuals are ready, you will get one.  If you dont
have ftp access and cant get the updates this way, two free (disk
based) updates are included in the shareware fee.  You have to contact
me everytime you want me to send you an upgrade.

You can send cash or international money order to

     Markus Moenig
     Bruesseler Ring 61
     52074 Aachen
     Germany
     Tel.: (49)-241-71844

If you prefer direct transfer:

     Markus Moenig
     NO. 20011672
     Stadtsparkasse Aachen
     BLZ 390 500 00 (Germany)
     Usage: MainActor
     PLEASE INCLUDE YOUR NAME ON THE TRANSFER ORDER !!

If you have questions/suggestions feel free to contact me through email:

     Fido        2:242/7.13
     Internet    moenig@pool.informatik.rwth-aachen.de
     ADSP        markusm@tolkien.adsp.sub.org


@EndNode

@Node "The Future" "MainActor.guide/The Future"
@Next "Credits"
@Prev "Registration"
@Toc "Main"

The Future
**********

Future enhancements which are on my list:

   - an animation loader/saver for VRLIs Vista Pro format (VANIM)

   - mpeg and Jpeg loader

   - more picture and animation modules (in general)

   - user defineable shortcuts ala TurboText

   - support of more 24 Bit modules, for example more modules for
     graphiccards

   - more powerful arexx commands (for example : syncing arexx commands
     to animations)

   - far more arexx scripts (sinus (de)-acceleration scripts and more)

   - German documentation

   - sending printed manuals to registered users

   - the whole MultiMedia stuff ...

   In the long run i want to make a complete @{b}MultiMedia@{ub} package out of
MainActor with Sound and Effect modules.  The planned sample per frame
option is the first step in that direction, instead of integrating the
samples in the animations/pictures itself, there will be a new module
type : Sound.  You will be able to associate sound modules to every
frame/picture. Sound modules could for example be samples or protracker
play routines.


@EndNode

